"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Psalms chapters 28–33
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-psalms-28-33.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/psalms.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/psalms.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/psalms.json (continuity)

Key Christological decisions in this range:
- Ps 28:8 "his anointed one (meshiho)" — direct Messianic title; the strength YHWH is to
  his anointed prefigures the Father-Son relationship of mutual empowerment.
- Ps 29 sevenfold "voice of the LORD" — the divine Word/Logos structure; the voice that
  shook Sinai (Heb 12:26) is the same voice that calmed the sea (Mark 4:39) and is the
  Son through whom God speaks (Heb 1:2). The "glory" cried in YHWH's temple (v9) anticipates
  the heavenly worship of the Lamb (Rev 5:12-13).
- Ps 30 superscription "Dedication of the Temple" — used at Hanukkah (temple rededication);
  Christ as the true temple (John 2:19-21). The death-and-resurrection pattern (vv. 1-3)
  is one of the OT's clearest resurrection typologies; the "night of weeping / morning of joy"
  (v5) is the paschal pattern.
- Ps 31:5 "Into your hand I commit my spirit" — Luke 23:46 DIRECT CITATION: Jesus's
  final words from the cross. The most explicit passion-narrative citation in this range.
- Ps 32:1-2 — DIRECT CITATION in Romans 4:7-8: Paul quotes both verses as the OT
  proof that justification is by faith/imputation, not works. The forgiveness described
  is the imputation of righteousness that Romans 4 says Abraham received and that comes
  through Christ (Rom 4:24-25; 2 Cor 5:21).
- Ps 33:6 "heavens made by the word of the LORD... breath of his mouth" — the creation-
  through-the-Word anticipates John 1:1-3 ("through him all things were made") and the
  Trinitarian structure of creation (Word + Spirit/Breath).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-christ for Psalms 28-33 — individual lament (Ps 28/31), theophany (Ps 29),
#   resurrection-patterned thanksgiving (Ps 30), penitential justification-by-faith (Ps 32),
#   and creation-by-the-Word praise (Ps 33); two direct NT citations (Ps 31:5/Luke 23:46;
#   Ps 32:1-2/Rom 4:7-8).
# CHANGE? If commentary/mkt-christ/psalms.json structure changes, update load_comm/save_comm.
# VERIFY: python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-christ/psalms.json'));
#   [print(ch, len(d[ch])) for ch in ['28','29','30','31','32','33']]"

PSALMS = {
  "28": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: the psalmist\'s cry to "my Rock" establishes the pattern of the righteous sufferer calling on YHWH in silence — and the cry that will not be answered by silence is the cry that grounds the NT\'s confidence in prayer. 1 Corinthians 10:4 identifies the rock that accompanied Israel as Christ himself; Psalm 28\'s "my Rock, do not be deaf to me" is the prayer directed toward the one who is both the foundation of all prayer and its ultimate answer. The terror of divine silence — "if you remain silent, I will be like those who go down to the pit" — captures the existential stakes of the cross, when the one who prayed "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?" experienced the anguished version of this fear.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: lifting hands toward the Most Holy Place (<em>devir</em>) — the innermost sanctuary housing the ark-throne — is the prayer posture that the entire Levitical system made available to Israel. Christ fulfills this gesture as the great high priest who entered the true Most Holy Place by means of his own blood (Heb 9:11-12, 24-26), making effective the approach that the lifted hands of the psalmist could only symbolize. The prayer that rises toward the earthly <em>devir</em> now rises through the heavenly high priest who stands permanently in the presence of God on behalf of those who call to him (Heb 7:25).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "speak peace to their neighbors while plotting evil in their hearts" — the psalm\'s description of the wicked who use words of peace to conceal hearts of violence identifies precisely the kind of duplicity that Christ repudiated throughout his ministry (Matt 15:8: "this people honors me with their lips, but their hearts are far from me"). Christ himself is the inverse: his words of peace are expressions of a heart that is entirely for the good of those he addresses. The distinction between the righteous sufferer (the psalmist, and ultimately Christ) and those who speak peace while plotting evil is the moral contrast that the entire passion narrative makes visible.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: the imprecation against the wicked — "pay them back for what they have done" — stands within the covenant framework where YHWH is the judge who repays. The NT does not repudiate divine judgment but relocates and extends its scope: the wrath that the wicked deserve has fallen on Christ at the cross (Rom 3:25-26; 2 Cor 5:21), and the judgment that remains is the final judgment of the last day. The psalmist\'s prayer for just repayment is not vindictiveness but covenant realism: the moral order of the universe requires that wrong be answered with consequence. Christ\'s atonement is the answer to the same moral logic — not its elimination but its satisfaction at infinite cost.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "they take no account of the LORD\'s works" — the blindness to divine activity that results in destruction. The pattern runs throughout the OT (Isa 5:12: "they do not regard the deeds of the LORD, or see the work of his hands") and is fulfilled in those who failed to recognize Christ\'s signs and wonders as divine works (John 12:37: "though he had performed so many signs in their presence, they still would not believe in him"). To take no account of divine works is ultimately to miss the greatest divine work — the incarnation, death, and resurrection of the Son.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "Praise the LORD! For he has heard my cry for mercy" — the pivot from lament to praise that structures the individual lament genre and the entire gospel narrative. The cry that is heard is the pattern of the cross-and-resurrection: the crucified one\'s cry (Ps 22:24) is answered by the resurrection. Hebrews 5:7 applies this directly to Christ: "In the days of his flesh, Jesus offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears, to him who was able to save him from death, and he was heard because of his reverence." The same YHWH who heard the psalmist heard the incarnate Son; the pivot from lament to praise is the paschal movement.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "The LORD is my strength and my shield; my heart trusts in him and I am helped; my heart leaps for joy, and with my song I give thanks to him." The experience of help received that produces trust confirmed and joy expressed is the movement of faith through suffering to vindication. Ephesians 6:16 identifies "the shield of faith" as armor against the enemy\'s attacks; Ps 28:7\'s "shield" is the covenant protection that faith grasps as already present. The sequence — strength, shield, trust, help, joy, thanks — maps the spiritual journey from vulnerability through faith to doxology that the NT presents as the normal pattern of Christian suffering (Rom 5:3-5; 2 Cor 4:17).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct anticipation: "The LORD is the strength of his people; he is the saving fortress of his <em>anointed one</em> (<em>meshiho</em>)." The Messianic title appears explicitly: YHWH is the strength of and salvation for his <em>mashiach</em> (anointed one). In the royal psalms, the anointed one is the Davidic king whom YHWH supports; in the NT\'s canonical reading, this support-relationship between YHWH and his anointed is the pattern of the Father\'s support of the Son. The resurrection is the supreme instance of YHWH being the "saving fortress" of his anointed: the one who died is raised and vindicated by the Father (Acts 2:36; Phil 2:9-11).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "Save your people and bless your heritage; be their shepherd and carry them forever." The shepherd who carries his people — the divine shepherd of Israel — is fulfilled in Christ, who calls himself the Good Shepherd (John 10:11), who carries the lost sheep on his shoulders (Luke 15:5), and who is identified as the "great Shepherd of the sheep" by the blood of the eternal covenant (Heb 13:20). "Carry them forever" anticipates the eternal shepherding of Rev 7:17: "the Lamb at the center of the throne will be their shepherd; he will lead them to springs of living water." The prayer of v9 receives its complete answer only in the eschatological shepherd-community of the new creation.</p>',
  },
  "29": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "Ascribe to the LORD, O heavenly beings (<em>bene elim</em>), ascribe to the LORD glory and strength." The heavenly beings summoned to worship — the divine council, the angelic host, the "sons of God" of Gen 6:2 and Job 1:6 — are called to direct their worship to YHWH. The NT extends this command to its Christological fulfillment: Heb 1:6 (citing Ps 97:7 LXX) says that at the introduction of the firstborn into the world, God commands: "Let all God\'s angels worship him." The worship that Psalm 29 commands the heavenly beings to direct to YHWH is commanded in Hebrews to be directed toward the Son — the strongest NT statement of Christ\'s divine identity.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Give the LORD the glory due his name; worship the LORD in the splendor of his holiness." The "glory due his name" — the <em>kavod</em> that properly belongs to YHWH — is what the NT presents as belonging to Christ. John 17:5 (Jesus: "glorify me in your presence with the glory I had with you before the world began"), John 12:41 (Isaiah saw Christ\'s glory in the Isa 6 throne-vision), and the heavenly doxologies of Revelation (5:12-13; 7:12) all extend the "glory due his name" to include Christ within the identity of the divine name. Psalm 29\'s call to worship in the "splendor of holiness" is ultimately a call to recognize and worship the God who is fully revealed in Christ.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "The voice of the LORD is over the waters; the God of glory thunders — the LORD, over mighty waters." The "voice of the LORD" (<em>qol YHWH</em>) repeated seven times in this psalm is the thunderous divine speech that governs creation and history. The NT\'s deepest engagement with this image is the identification of Christ as the divine Word/Logos (John 1:1-3): the voice of the LORD through whom creation came into being is the same Word who became flesh. At Jesus\'s baptism, the Father\'s voice speaks from heaven over the waters of the Jordan (Matt 3:17; Mark 1:11; Luke 3:22) — the "voice of the LORD over the waters" given its ultimate specification: "This is my Son, whom I love."</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "The voice of the LORD is powerful; the voice of the LORD is majestic." The paired attributes — power (<em>koah</em>) and majesty (<em>hadar</em>) — of the divine voice are the attributes the NT assigns to Christ\'s own voice and word. Matthew 7:28-29: "the crowds were amazed at his teaching, because he taught as one who had authority (<em>exousia</em>), and not as their teachers of the law." Revelation 1:15 describes the risen Christ\'s voice as "like the sound of rushing waters" — the same awesome magnitude as the voice of the LORD over the waters in Psalm 29. The majestic, powerful divine voice becomes incarnate and audible in the teaching and commands of Jesus.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "The voice of the LORD shatters the cedars; the LORD shatters the cedars of Lebanon." The cedars of Lebanon were the symbol of human pride and greatness in the ancient Near East — the most magnificent trees, used for royal palaces and great temples (1 Kgs 5:6; 7:2; Isa 2:13; 10:34). The divine voice that shatters what human greatness most prizes is the voice that Isaiah 40:6-8 describes as reducing all flesh to withering grass — "but the word of our God stands forever." Christ embodies and speaks this word: "Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away" (Matt 24:35). The voice that shatters cedar is also the voice that cannot be silenced even by death.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "He makes Lebanon skip like a calf, and Sirion like a young wild ox." The cosmic playfulness of the divine theophany — mountains "skipping" before the divine voice — reveals YHWH\'s sovereign relationship to the created order: even the most massive geological features are as lightweight before divine presence as calves before a human spectator. The NT\'s equivalent is Christ\'s sovereign authority over natural forces: calming the storm (Mark 4:39: the wind and sea obey his voice), walking on water (Mark 6:48-50), and the eschatological shaking of the heavens and earth at his return (Heb 12:26-27, citing Hag 2:6). The creation that skips playfully before the divine voice in Ps 29 trembles before the returning Son of Man in the Gospels.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "The voice of the LORD strikes with flashes of lightning." Lightning as the weapon of divine speech and action — the divine voice made visible in the storm (Ps 18:14; 97:4; 144:6). The book of Revelation presents the throne of God with "flashes of lightning, rumblings and peals of thunder" (Rev 4:5), connecting the theophanic storm of Psalm 29 to the heavenly worship scene. The judgment-lightning associated with divine speech becomes, in the eschatological vision, the accompaniment of the Lamb who shares the divine throne. The voice that is lightning in Psalm 29 is the same voice that will judge the world at the last day (John 5:22, 27: "the Father has given all judgment to the Son").</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "The voice of the LORD shakes the wilderness; the LORD shakes the wilderness of Kadesh." The wilderness of Kadesh was the southern boundary of the promised land — where Israel wandered and where divine judgment fell (Num 20). The divine voice that "shakes the wilderness" (same verb as Heb 12:26\'s "I will shake the heavens and the earth once more") is the voice whose eschatological shaking Hebrews applies to the final judgment. Christ\'s voice is the agent of that final shaking: at his first coming he shook the wilderness of human sin by his presence; at his return he will shake all that can be shaken so that only the unshakeable kingdom remains (Heb 12:27-28).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "The voice of the LORD causes the deer to writhe in labor and strips the forests bare; and in his temple all cry, \'Glory!\'" The creation\'s involuntary response to the divine voice — the laboring deer, the stripped forests — gives way to the temple\'s unanimous cry of "glory" (<em>kavod</em>). In Revelation 5:12-13, the heavenly temple\'s doxology is directed to the Lamb: "Worthy is the Lamb who was slain, to receive power and wealth and wisdom and strength and honor and glory and praise!" The "glory" cry of the earthly temple in Ps 29:9 reaches its eschatological form when the heavenly temple\'s entire population directs it to the crucified and risen Christ.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "The LORD sat enthroned over the Flood; the LORD sits enthroned as King forever." The divine throne above the flood-waters (Gen 6-8; Ps 93:1-4) — YHWH\'s sovereignty over the chaos that threatened to undo creation — is exercised permanently ("King forever"). The NT applies this sovereign enthronement to Christ: the calming of the storm (Mark 4:39-41: "even the wind and the waves obey him!") is the disciples\' first encounter with the one who sits enthroned above the waters; the resurrection and ascension are the demonstration that his kingship is permanent. Acts 2:33-36 announces the ascended Christ\'s enthronement at the right hand of the Father — the permanent Kingship of Ps 29:10 given its final address.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: "The LORD gives strength to his people; the LORD blesses his people with peace." The closing benediction of the theophanic psalm: the God whose voice terrifies the cosmos gives strength and peace to his covenant community. Christ embodies both gifts: in John 14:27, he gives his peace — "not as the world gives" — specifically to the disciples who are about to face the storm of his arrest and death. In Luke 24:49, he promises the "power (<em>dynamis</em>) from on high" — the strength the disciples will need after Pentecost. The terrifying divine voice of Psalm 29 is the same God who speaks peace and grants strength to those who are his — and the one through whom both blessings come is Christ.</p>',
  },
  "30": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: the psalm\'s superscription — "a Song for the Dedication of the Temple" (<em>hanukat habayit</em>) — connects it to the rededication celebration; the Maccabean rededication of the defiled temple (165 BCE) gave rise to Hanukkah, and this psalm was central to that liturgy. Christ declared himself the true temple (John 2:19-21: "destroy this temple and I will raise it again in three days"); the "dedication" of the temple that the psalm celebrates becomes, in Christ, the dedication of the ultimate dwelling of God with humanity — accomplished through his death and resurrection. "I exalt you, O LORD, for you have lifted me up and have not let my enemies triumph over me" — the exaltation/lifting-up language that John\'s Gospel uses for the crucifixion-and-resurrection (John 3:14; 8:28; 12:32).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A shadow: "O LORD my God, I cried to you for help, and you healed me." The healing of the psalmist — rescue from whatever mortal crisis threatened him — is one of the OT\'s paradigmatic images of divine rescue that the NT fulfills at the deepest level. Hebrews 5:7 applies the pattern of crying-for-help to Christ: "In the days of his flesh, Jesus offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears, to him who was able to save him from death, and he was heard." The healing/rescue in Psalm 30 points forward to the resurrection as the ultimate divine response to the cry of the righteous sufferer in mortal danger.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct anticipation: "LORD, you brought my soul up from the realm of the dead (<em>sheol</em>); you restored my life from among those who descend to the pit (<em>bor</em>)." This verse is the OT\'s most direct description of resurrection language applied to the individual before the NT. The experience it describes — being pulled back from the edge of death by divine action — becomes the template for understanding Christ\'s resurrection. Peter\'s Pentecost sermon (Acts 2:27-31) cites Ps 16:10 in the same pattern ("you will not abandon me to the realm of the dead"); the logic of Ps 30:3 is the same: YHWH does not abandon the righteous one to <em>sheol</em>. The resurrection of Christ is the final, literal fulfillment of the pattern that this verse typologically establishes.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "Sing praises to the LORD, O you his faithful ones (<em>hasidav</em>), and give thanks to his holy name." The call to corporate praise is grounded in the individual rescue (vv. 1-3) but addressed to the community. The "holy name" that is thanked — the divine identity as revealed in covenant history — becomes in the NT the name of Jesus, in whom all the divine covenant-faithfulness is concentrated. Acts 4:12 ("there is no other name under heaven given to mankind by which we must be saved"), Phil 2:10 ("at the name of Jesus every knee should bow"), and Rev 15:4 ("all nations will come and worship before you, for your righteous acts have been revealed") all extend the "give thanks to his holy name" to its Christological fullness.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct anticipation: "For his anger lasts only a moment, but his favor lasts a lifetime; weeping may remain through the night, but joy arrives with the morning." The night-of-weeping and morning-of-joy pattern is one of the OT\'s most precise anticipations of the paschal mystery. The crucifixion was on a Friday (the night that descended); the resurrection was at dawn on Sunday (the morning that arrived). John 20:1 — "early on the first day of the week, while it was still dark, Mary Magdalene went to the tomb" — and the subsequent "Joy arrives with the morning" reversal are the literal fulfillment of Ps 30:5\'s pattern. The "moment" of divine anger (the cross, where the wrath due sin was borne) gives way to the "lifetime" of divine favor (the resurrection life and the age to come).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "When I was prosperous, I said, \'I will never be shaken.\'" The false confidence of the psalmist in his own prosperity — the conviction that the good times will continue indefinitely — is the spiritual error that the NT consistently warns against. Luke 12:19 (the rich fool: "you have plenty of grain laid up for many years") is the parable Jesus tells of the same false security. The psalmist\'s self-deception in prosperity is a theme that Christ\'s teaching consistently addresses: "Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth..." (Matt 6:19). The verse serves as the setup for the theological correction of vv. 7-12: prosperity without YHWH\'s sustaining favor is always precarious.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "By your favor, LORD, you had made my mountain stand firm; when you hid your face, I was terrified." The divine hiding of the face — <em>hester panim</em> — is the OT\'s most acute description of the experience of divine abandonment. Psalm 22:24 uses the same concept ("he has not despised or scorned the suffering of the afflicted one; he has not hidden his face from him"). Christ\'s cry from the cross (Matt 27:46: "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?") is the ultimate instance of the hidden face — the one who had known the fullness of the Father\'s face (John 1:18) experiencing in his flesh the terror of divine hiddenness that the psalmist describes here.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "To you, LORD, I called out; to the Lord I made my appeal" — the prayer of the righteous sufferer in crisis, addressed upward to the only one who can help. The Gethsemane prayer (Matt 26:36-46; Luke 22:41-44) is the NT\'s fullest instance of the pattern: "My Father, if it is possible, may this cup be taken from me. Yet not as I will, but as you will." The directness and urgency of the appeal — calling and making supplication — is the posture of the one who has no other resource. Hebrews 5:7 (Jesus "offered up prayers and supplications with loud cries and tears") confirms that Christ entered fully into the posture of v8.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "What is gained if I die and go down to the grave? Can the dust praise you? Can it proclaim your faithfulness?" The pragmatic argument from the value of life for worship: the dead cannot praise. The psalmist uses this logic as an argument for rescue — YHWH has an interest in the psalmist\'s survival because the dead do not produce doxology. The resurrection is the ultimate answer to this question: Christ\'s resurrection is precisely the demonstration that death does not end praise. The risen Christ leads his brethren in worship (Heb 2:12: "I will declare your name to my brothers and sisters; in the assembly I will sing your praises"), accomplishing from the other side of death what the psalmist could only argue for.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "Hear me, LORD, and have mercy on me! LORD, be my helper!" — the cry for mercy and help that characterizes the lament tradition\'s approach to God. Christ is identified in the NT as the one who responds to exactly this cry: "he is able to deal gently with those who are ignorant and are going astray" (Heb 5:2); "let us then approach God\'s throne of grace with confidence, so that we may receive mercy and find grace to help us in our time of need" (Heb 4:16). The "helper" that the psalmist cries for becomes, in the NT, a Christological title: Christ as the one who "is at the right hand of God and is also interceding for us" (Rom 8:34).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A shadow: "You have turned my mourning into dancing; you have removed my sackcloth and clothed me with joy." The clothing metaphor for the reversal of fortune — sackcloth (mourning garments) replaced by joyful garments — is a recurring OT image of eschatological transformation (Isa 61:3: "to bestow on them a crown of beauty instead of ashes, the oil of joy instead of mourning, and a garment of praise instead of a spirit of despair"). Christ applies Isa 61:1-2 to himself in Luke 4:18-19; the transformation of mourning into dancing that Psalm 30:11 celebrates is the enacted pattern of the gospel. The Easter morning transformation — from the mourning of the disciples on Holy Saturday to the joy of resurrection Sunday — is the fullest historical instance of this verse.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A shadow: "so that my spirit may sing your praise and not be silent. O LORD my God, I will give you thanks forever." The commitment to eternal thanksgiving — "forever" — is the logical conclusion of rescue from death: the one who has been pulled back from <em>sheol</em> will praise without end. The eternal worship of the redeemed community in Revelation (7:9-12; 15:3-4; 19:1-7) is the communal fulfillment of the individual\'s "I will give you thanks forever." Christ himself leads this eternal praise (Heb 2:12; Rev 5:9-10); the resurrection that the psalm celebrates produces the eternal doxology that the consummation will be filled with.</p>',
  },
  "31": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "In you, LORD, I take refuge; let me never be put to shame (<em>avushah</em>); rescue me by your righteousness." The covenant refuge-and-righteousness structure — taking shelter in YHWH and being rescued by his <em>tzedakah</em> (righteous deliverance) — is the OT template for the NT\'s doctrine of justification. Romans 1:17 ("in the gospel the righteousness of God is revealed") and Philippians 3:9 ("not having a righteousness of my own... but that which is through faith in Christ") develop the "rescued by your righteousness" of Ps 31:1 to its fulfillment. "Let me never be put to shame" — the covenant promise that faith in YHWH is not ultimately disappointed — is what Paul says of Christ: "anyone who trusts in him will never be put to shame" (Rom 10:11, citing Isa 28:16).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Turn your ear to me; quickly rescue me. Be my rock of refuge, a strong fortress to save me." The petition for a "rock of refuge" continues the rock-theology of Ps 28:1 ("my Rock"). 1 Corinthians 10:4 identifies the accompanying rock as Christ; the rock-fortress that the psalmist petitions YHWH to be is the salvation that Christ provides. Matthew 7:24-25 (building on the rock that does not fall) applies rock-foundation imagery to obedience to Christ\'s words — the same "rock of refuge" language, with Christ as both the rock and the one who points toward it.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "For you are my rock and my fortress; lead me and guide me for your name\'s sake." "For your name\'s sake" — the divine motivation for guiding and rescuing is the divine reputation: the name of YHWH is at stake in the fate of his servant. The same logic applies in the NT to Christ\'s work: Eph 1:12-14 ("for the praise of his glory"); Phil 2:9-11 ("the name that is above every name... to the glory of God the Father"). The guidance "for the name\'s sake" becomes in the NT the whole economy of salvation, conducted "to the praise of his glorious grace" (Eph 1:6).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "Free me from the trap they have secretly set for me, for you are my refuge." The hidden trap — the secret plot against the righteous sufferer — is the pattern that the passion narratives develop in their accounts of the secret plots against Jesus (Mark 14:1: "the chief priests and the teachers of the law were scheming to arrest Jesus secretly and kill him"; Luke 22:2: "they were afraid of the people"). Psalm 31:4\'s prayer for freedom from the secretly set trap is the prayer that the psalm\'s trajectory will ultimately answer through resurrection: the trap was sprung (the arrest, trial, death) but did not hold, because "the LORD is the refuge" whose deliverance cannot be permanently thwarted.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct citation: "Into your hand I commit my spirit (<em>beyad-kha afkid ruhi</em>); you have redeemed me, LORD, faithful God." Luke 23:46 — Jesus\'s final words from the cross — are an explicit quotation of this verse: "Jesus called out with a loud voice, \'Father, into your hands I commit my spirit.\' When he had said this, he breathed his last." Christ took the psalmist\'s prayer of trust in the moment of mortal crisis and made it his own dying breath. The original prayer is a statement of confidence in YHWH\'s faithfulness even in death; Jesus transforms it into the ultimate act of filial trust — the Son committing his spirit into the Father\'s hand. The addition of "Father" to the quotation deepens the Sonship dimension: what was a covenant servant\'s prayer becomes the Son\'s surrender to the Father.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "I despise those who cling to worthless idols; but I trust in the LORD." The double movement — repudiating false trust and affirming true trust — is the structure of the covenant\'s exclusive loyalty. Jonah 2:8 echoes this ("those who cling to worthless idols forfeit the grace that could be theirs"), suggesting the phrase was formulaic covenant language. Christ\'s exclusive loyalty to the Father throughout his ministry — "I always do what pleases him" (John 8:29) — is the fullest embodiment of this covenant faithfulness. The "trust in the LORD" that the psalmist affirms against the background of worthless alternatives is what Christ models completely in the Gethsemane prayer: "not as I will, but as you will" (Matt 26:39).</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "I will be glad and rejoice in your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>), for you have seen my distress and known the anguish of my soul." The divine seeing and knowing of the sufferer\'s distress — the intimate divine knowledge that precedes rescue — is the theological claim that the incarnation fulfills in its deepest form. Hebrews 4:15: "we do not have a high priest who is unable to empathize with our weaknesses, but we have one who has been tempted in every way, just as we are." Christ\'s incarnation is the ultimate divine "knowing the anguish of the soul" — not from outside but from within human experience. The gladness in covenant love that the psalmist anticipates upon rescue is the joy that "was set before him" that enabled Christ to endure the cross (Heb 12:2).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "you did not hand me over to the enemy; you set my feet in a wide-open place." The "wide-open place" (<em>merahav</em>, spacious place, room, relief from constriction) — the rescue from the narrow passage of danger into open space — is the salvation image that Paul uses in 2 Cor 6:11-12 (the "open heart") and that the whole NT uses for the freedom of the gospel (Gal 5:1: "It is for freedom that Christ has set us free"). The constriction of death, law, and sin from which the psalmist is delivered anticipates the comprehensive liberation that Christ\'s resurrection accomplishes: "where the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom" (2 Cor 3:17).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "Have mercy on me, LORD, for I am in trouble; my eye wastes with grief — my soul and my body too." The total somatic experience of suffering — eye, soul, and body all wasting together — is the holistic human crisis that requires holistic divine rescue. The incarnation is the divine response to holistic human suffering: Christ took on body, soul, and spirit (not merely a human appearance) precisely in order to rescue the whole person. Hebrews 2:17-18 makes the logic explicit: "he had to be made like them, fully human in every way... because he himself suffered when he was tempted, he is able to help those who are being tempted." The suffering body-and-soul of Ps 31:9 is the suffering that the incarnate Son entered in order to redeem.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "For my life is exhausted by grief and my years by sighing; my strength fails because of my iniquity, and my bones waste away." The connection of physical exhaustion to moral failure ("my strength fails because of my iniquity") is the OT\'s recognition that sin and suffering are connected — not as simple cause-and-effect (Job\'s friends\' error) but as covenantal reality (the whole-person disruption that sin causes). Isaiah 53:3-4 uses the same imagery for the Servant: "a man of suffering... he took up our pain and bore our suffering." Christ bore not only the judicial consequence of iniquity (Rom 3:25) but its physical exhaustion (John 19:28: "knowing that everything had now been finished... Jesus said, \'I am thirsty\'").</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: "Among all my enemies I am an object of scorn, and especially to my neighbors; those who know me are afraid — when people see me in the street, they flee from me." The social abandonment and mockery of the righteous sufferer — scorned by enemies, fled from by acquaintances — is the passion narrative in embryo. Mark 14:50: "then everyone deserted him and fled"; Matt 27:39-44: the passers-by, the chief priests, and those crucified with him all mocked. The "object of scorn" (<em>herpah</em>) of Ps 31:11 is the same word used in Pss 69:7, 9, 10, 19, 20 — all applied to Christ in the NT (Rom 15:3; John 2:17; Rom 15:3).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: "I am as forgotten as a dead man; I have become like a shattered clay vessel." The image of being as forgotten as a dead man — the socially disappeared, the one whose name is no longer spoken — is the nadir of honor-shame experience. The "shattered clay vessel" (<em>keli oved</em>) is the discarded pot, broken and thrown away. The passion narrative\'s extreme: Jesus died in disgrace, was buried in another man\'s tomb, and could have been forgotten. But Isaiah 53:12 says "he poured out his life unto death" in a way that resulted in his receiving "a portion among the great" — the shattered vessel is raised to glory (Phil 2:8-9). The "forgotten dead man" who is raised becomes the one of whom it is said "he ever lives to intercede" (Heb 7:25).</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: "I hear the rumors of the many — terror surrounds me — as they plot together against me, conspiring to take my life." The conspiracy against the life of the righteous sufferer is the passion narrative\'s political-religious structure: the "rumors of the many" (the crowd calling for crucifixion), the plots of the Sanhedrin (John 11:53: "from that day on they plotted to take his life"), and the terror of being surrounded. Psalm 31:13 is part of the complex of Passion Psalms (Pss 22, 31, 69) that the Gospel writers drew on to interpret and narrate the events of Good Friday as the fulfillment of the OT pattern of the righteous sufferer.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme: "But I trusted in you, LORD; I said, \'You are my God.\'" The "but" that pivots from the surrounding terror (v13) to the confession of trust is the theological hinge of the entire psalm — and of the passion narrative. Luke 23:46 (Christ\'s dying words from Ps 31:5) comes immediately after the darkness and the tearing of the temple veil, but the dying breath is an act of trust. The pivot from surrounding hostility to covenant trust ("you are my God") is what distinguished Christ\'s death from the deaths of those crucified beside him: in the same circumstances of abandonment and humiliation, Christ confessed the Father.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A theme: "My times are in your hand; rescue me from my enemies and from those who pursue me." "My times are in your hand" — the divine sovereignty over the timing and circumstances of the sufferer\'s life — is the theological claim that the passion narrative embodies. John 7:30 ("no one laid a hand on him, because his hour had not yet come"); John 12:23 ("the hour has come for the Son of Man to be glorified"); John 17:1 ("Father, the hour has come"). Christ\'s times were in the Father\'s hand: the cross happened at the appointed time (Gal 4:4: "when the set time had fully come, God sent his Son"), and the resurrection was timed to the third day as Jesus himself repeatedly announced.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme: "Make your face shine on your servant; save me through your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>)." The priestly blessing of Num 6:24-26 ("the LORD make his face shine on you and be gracious to you") is the covenantal blessing invoked here in personal petition. Salvation "through steadfast love" is the covenant-mercy basis of all divine rescue — not earned by the servant but grounded in YHWH\'s committed covenant loyalty. The NT\'s development: "God demonstrates his own love for us in this: while we were still sinners, Christ died for us" (Rom 5:8). The face that shines in rescue is the face of God revealed in Christ (2 Cor 4:6: "the light of the knowledge of God\'s glory displayed in the face of Christ").</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme: "LORD, let me not be put to shame, for I have called on you; let the wicked be ashamed — let them go silently down to Sheol." The double shame petition — for the righteous not to be shamed and for the wicked to receive shame — is the covenant moral order enforced eschatologically. Romans 10:11 ("anyone who trusts in him will never be put to shame") applies this promise directly to those who trust in Christ. The "not put to shame" is the resurrection vindication: the crucified one who seemed to be shamed publicly (Heb 12:2: "enduring the cross, scorning its shame") is raised by the Father, vindicating him and demonstrating that trust in him was not misplaced.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "Let the lying lips be struck silent — lips that speak against the righteous with arrogance and contempt." The false witnesses and false accusations that surrounded Jesus\'s trial (Mark 14:56-59: "many bore false witness against him") are the literal fulfillment of the "lying lips that speak against the righteous." The prayer that they be struck silent is answered not in the trial itself (where they succeeded) but in the resurrection, which silenced the accusation finally: "who will bring any charge against those whom God has chosen? It is God who justifies" (Rom 8:33). The lying lips of the trial are answered by the divine verdict of the resurrection.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "How great is your goodness, which you have stored up for those who fear you and displayed for those who take shelter in you, in full view of all!" The "stored up" goodness — the eschatological reserve of divine blessing prepared for the covenant-faithful — is what Paul cites in 1 Corinthians 2:9 ("no eye has seen, no ear has heard, no mind has conceived what God has prepared for those who love him"). The goodness that the psalmist expects to be "displayed in full view of all" is the eschatological manifestation of the kingdom: "When Christ, who is your life, appears, then you also will appear with him in glory" (Col 3:4).</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme: "In the shelter of your presence you hide them from human plots; you conceal them in your tent from the quarreling of tongues." The divine shelter that hides the vulnerable from human schemes — the protective hiddenness in the divine presence — is the pattern that the NT expresses as being "hidden with Christ in God" (Col 3:3). The ultimate shelter is Christ himself: those who are in Christ are protected by the same divine presence that protects the covenant people in Psalm 31:20. Revelation 7:15 ("he who sits on the throne will shelter them with his presence") uses <em>skene</em> (tent/tabernacle), the same sheltering image, for the eschatological refuge of the redeemed.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme: "Praise the LORD, for he displayed his wonderful steadfast love to me when I was like a man in a besieged city." The "besieged city" image — the surrounded, enclosed, cut off — is the experience of utter isolation and helplessness from which YHWH\'s <em>hesed</em> rescues. The crucifixion created exactly this besieged-city condition for Jesus: surrounded by enemies, abandoned by friends, cut off. The praise that follows rescue from the besieged city is the Easter praise: "Christ has indeed been raised from the dead" (1 Cor 15:20). The <em>hesed</em> that is wonderful (<em>niflat hesdo</em>, his love working wonders/miracles) is the love that performs the miracle of resurrection.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: "I said in my panic, \'I am cut off from your sight.\' Yet you heard my cries for mercy when I called to you." The experience of being "cut off from sight" — the complete loss of the sense of divine presence — is the subjective experience of abandonment that the psalmist confesses was not the reality. The gap between felt abandonment and actual divine faithfulness is the space within which faith operates — and the space that the resurrection closes. Christ\'s cry on the cross ("my God, my God, why have you forsaken me?") gives voice to the felt abandonment of Ps 31:22; the resurrection is the answer that "yet you heard my cries for mercy" — the cry was not unheard, and the Forsaken One was not finally forsaken.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A theme: "Love the LORD, all you his faithful people! The LORD protects the faithful and pays back the proud in full." The summons to love YHWH grounded in the covenant confidence that faithfulness is protected and pride repaid is the ethical conclusion of the individual lament. The NT grounding for the same summons: 1 John 4:19 ("we love because he first loved us") — covenant love precedes and enables responsive love. "The LORD protects the faithful" becomes in the NT "I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish; no one will snatch them out of my hand" (John 10:28). Christ is both the one who models the faithfulness of vv. 1-22 and the one through whom the faithful are protected.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A theme: "Be strong, and let your heart be courageous, all you who hope in the LORD!" The closing call to courage grounded in hope is the community\'s appropriate response to everything the psalm has described: the suffering, the deliverance, the vindication. Hebrews 12:1-3 makes the same call from the same foundation: "run with perseverance the race marked out for us, fixing our eyes on Jesus... so that you will not grow weary and lose heart." The courage the psalmist summons is exactly the courage that "fixing our eyes on Jesus" enables — the resurrection confidence that makes present suffering bearable. The hope in YHWH of Ps 31:24 is the hope centered on Christ that "does not put us to shame, because God\'s love has been poured out into our hearts" (Rom 5:5).</p>',
  },
  "32": {
    "1": '<p>A direct citation: "Blessed is the one whose transgression is forgiven (<em>nesui-fesha</em>), whose sin is covered (<em>kesui hata\'ah</em>)." Romans 4:7-8 quotes Psalm 32:1-2 directly as the OT proof-text for justification by faith. Paul\'s argument: David (who wrote this psalm after his adultery and murder, by Jewish tradition) pronounces blessed not the person who has earned righteousness but the person whose sins are forgiven — demonstrating that even in the OT, blessing came through forgiveness/imputation, not works. The "covered" sin is covered by the atoning sacrifice that looks forward to Christ\'s atonement: the Levitical sin-coverings were types of the definitive covering accomplished at the cross (Heb 10:4-10, 12-14).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct citation: "Blessed is the man to whom the LORD does not reckon (<em>yehshov</em>) iniquity, and in whose spirit there is no deceit." Romans 4:8 quotes this verse explicitly. The word <em>hashav</em> (to reckon, count, impute) is the accounting language that Paul makes central to justification theology: the righteousness of Christ is "reckoned" to the believer (Rom 4:3, 5, 6, 9, 11, 22-24), and their sin is "not reckoned" against them. 2 Corinthians 5:19 ("not counting people\'s sins against them") uses exactly this logic: the one "through whom" this non-reckoning comes is Christ, in whom "God was reconciling the world to himself." The psalmist\'s beatitude of non-reckoned sin becomes, through Paul, the theological foundation of the gospel.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "When I kept silent about my sin, my bones wasted away through my constant groaning." The physical effect of unconfessed sin — the somatic experience of guilt held in — is the OT\'s recognition that the human body and spirit are not separate compartments. The NT\'s development: James 5:16 ("confess your sins to each other and pray for each other so that you may be healed — the prayer of a righteous person is powerful and effective"); 1 John 1:8-9 ("if we claim to be without sin, we deceive ourselves... if we confess our sins, he is faithful and just and will forgive us"). The wasting bones of unconfessed sin are healed by the same confession-and-forgiveness dynamic that the cross makes definitively available.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "Day and night your hand pressed down on me; my strength dried up like moisture in the summer heat." The divine pressure of conviction — YHWH\'s hand pressing down on the unconfessed sinner — is the gracious weight of the divine conscience: the discomfort of moral self-awareness that YHWH refuses to let the sinner escape. John 16:8-11: "When he comes, he will prove the world to be in the wrong about sin and righteousness and judgment" — the Spirit\'s convicting work is the NT form of the divine hand pressing down. The summer-heat dryness captures the exhaustion of guilt: a drought not of rainfall but of the spiritual vitality that divine presence supplies when sin is not the barrier.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "I made my sin known to you and did not hide my iniquity; I said, \'I will confess my transgressions to the LORD,\' and you forgave the guilt of my sin." The sequence — acknowledgment, unhiding, decision-to-confess, divine forgiveness — is the covenant structure of repentance and pardon that the NT specifies. 1 John 1:9 ("if we confess our sins, he is faithful and just and will forgive us our sins and purify us from all unrighteousness") is the direct NT parallel. The forgiveness is possible because of Christ\'s atonement: "the blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin" (1 John 1:7). Psalm 32:5\'s confession-and-forgiveness is the OT pattern whose NT mechanism is the cross.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "Therefore let every faithful person pray to you while you may still be found; when the great floodwaters surge, they will not reach them." The window of divine availability ("while you may still be found") is an urgency theme that Isaiah develops: "Seek the LORD while he may be found; call on him while he is near" (Isa 55:6). The NT\'s eschatological urgency is the same: "now is the time of God\'s favor, now is the day of salvation" (2 Cor 6:2); the great flood of judgment that will come (Matt 24:37-39 — the coming of the Son of Man compared to Noah\'s flood) will not reach those who have found shelter in YHWH\'s forgiveness. Christ himself is the ark: those who are "in Christ" are sheltered when the floodwaters surge.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "You are my hiding place; you guard me from trouble; you surround me with songs of rescue." The "hiding place" (<em>seter</em>) — the protective concealment in divine presence — is an image developed in Ps 91:1 ("whoever dwells in the shelter of the Most High") and fulfilled in the NT\'s "hidden with Christ in God" (Col 3:3). The "songs of rescue (<em>rannot palet</em>, shouts of deliverance)" that surround the rescued one anticipate the heavenly worship of the redeemed: Rev 15:3-4 (the song of Moses and of the Lamb — the song of deliverance). Christ is both the hiding place and the one who leads the songs of deliverance (Heb 2:12: "I will sing your praises").</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "I will instruct you and show you the way you should walk; I will guide you with my eye on you." The divine speaker (likely YHWH responding to the psalmist\'s confession and praise) promises personal instruction and guidance. The NT fulfills this at two levels: (1) Christ as teacher — "you have one Teacher, the Messiah" (Matt 23:10); "I am the way and the truth and the life" (John 14:6); and (2) the Spirit as the guide into all truth (John 16:13: "when he, the Spirit of truth, comes, he will guide you into all the truth"). The instruction "with my eye on you" is the personalized guidance that the Good Shepherd provides: "his sheep follow him because they know his voice" (John 10:4).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "Do not be like a horse or mule that lacks understanding and must be controlled with bit and bridle, or it will not come near you." The teaching-metaphor of vv. 8-9 contrasts the willing disciple (who follows by understanding) with the reluctant animal (that must be forced). Jesus\'s call to discipleship assumes willing response: "come, follow me" (Mark 1:17) — not compulsion but invitation. Yet the NT also recognizes human recalcitrance: "O Jerusalem, Jerusalem... how often I have longed to gather your children together, as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and you were not willing" (Matt 23:37). The contrast of willing vs. forced following is the contrast between grace received and grace resisted.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "The wicked have many sorrows, but steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>) surrounds those who trust in the LORD." The contrasting destinies — many sorrows for the wicked, covenant love encircling the trusting — frame the NT\'s doctrine of assurance. Romans 8:38-39 describes the encircling of the believers by divine love in the fullest NT terms: "neither death nor life, neither angels nor demons... will be able to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord." The <em>hesed</em> that "surrounds" in Ps 32:10 is personified and embodied in Christ: Eph 3:18-19 (grasping "how wide and long and high and deep is the love of Christ").</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: "Be glad in the LORD and rejoice, you righteous people! Shout for joy, all who are upright in heart!" The concluding doxological call — to be glad in the LORD and shout for joy — is the appropriate response to the entire psalm\'s movement: from unconfessed sin through conviction through confession through forgiveness through protection through instruction to joy. Philippians 4:4 ("rejoice in the Lord always; I will say it again: rejoice!") is the NT\'s sustained echo of this call. The joy is "in the LORD" (<em>baYHWH</em>) — not circumstantial joy but joy grounded in the covenant relationship with the God who forgives. In Christ, the ground of that joy is permanently established: the atonement that makes forgiveness available is a completed, unrepeatable act (Heb 10:12-14).</p>',
  },
  "33": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "Shout for joy in the LORD, you righteous! Praise is beautiful from those who are upright." The opening assertion — that praise is <em>naʾvāh</em> (beautiful, fitting, appropriate) from the righteous — raises the question of who the truly righteous are. The NT\'s answer: "there is no one righteous, not even one" (Rom 3:10-12, citing Ps 14:1-3/53:1-3), and yet "through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous" (Rom 5:19). The praise that is "beautiful from the righteous" becomes, in Christ, beautiful from those who have been made righteous through him — the imputed righteousness of faith enabling the praise that Psalm 33 calls for.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Praise the LORD with the lyre; make music to him with the ten-stringed harp." The instrumental dimension of covenant worship — lyre and harp in service of YHWH\'s praise — anticipates the heavenly worship of Revelation, where the twenty-four elders hold "harps given them by God" and sing (Rev 5:8-9; 14:2-3; 15:2-3). The music of creation-praise in Ps 33:2 reaches its eschatological fullness in the "new song" of the Lamb (Rev 5:9), where the instrumental and vocal elements of temple worship are transposed into the eternal worship of the new creation.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "Sing him a new song (<em>shir hadash</em>); play with skill and shout for joy." The "new song" formula appears elsewhere in the Psalter at creation-praise and salvation-praise moments (Pss 40:3; 96:1; 98:1; 144:9; 149:1; Isa 42:10) and reaches its fullest form in Revelation\'s eschatological worship. Revelation 5:9 — the twenty-four elders singing a "new song" to the Lamb — is explicitly the new song of redemption: "because you were slain, and with your blood you purchased for God persons from every tribe and language and people and nation." The new song that creation-praise calls for can only be sung by those redeemed through the cross.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "For the word of the LORD (<em>devar YHWH</em>) is right and true; all his works are done in faithfulness." The "word of the LORD" that is right and true is the same <em>Logos</em> that John 1:1 identifies as the pre-incarnate Christ: "the Word was with God, and the Word was God." Christ, as the divine Word, is the embodiment of the rightness and truth that Ps 33:4 attributes to YHWH\'s word. John 14:6 ("I am the way and the truth and the life") and Rev 19:11, 13 (the rider called "Faithful and True" and "the Word of God") describe the incarnate Word as the personal embodiment of the reliability that this verse attributes to divine speech.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "He loves righteousness and justice; the earth is full of the LORD\'s steadfast love." The divine love of righteousness and justice — the moral character of YHWH — is the character that Jesus embodies fully. Luke 4:18-19 (Jesus citing Isa 61:1-2) describes his ministry as bringing justice to the poor; Matt 12:18-21 (citing Isa 42:1-4) applies to Christ the promise that "he will proclaim justice to the nations." "The earth is full of his steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>)" — what fills the earth in Ps 33:5 is what the earth will be filled with when the knowledge of the LORD covers it as the waters cover the sea (Isa 11:9), the eschatological fullness that Christ\'s kingdom brings.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct anticipation: "The heavens were made by the word of the LORD (<em>devar YHWH</em>), and all their host by the breath of his mouth." This is the OT\'s most concentrated expression of creation through the divine Word — and the clearest anticipation of John 1:1-3: "In the beginning was the Word... through him all things were made; without him nothing was made that has been made." Colossians 1:16 ("all things were created through him and for him") and Hebrews 1:2 ("through whom also he made the universe") both develop this verse\'s identification of the Word/Son as the agent of creation. The "breath of his mouth" anticipates the Trinitarian structure of creation: the Word (Son) and the Spirit (breath/ruah) together bring all things into existence.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "He gathers the sea\'s waters like a heap; he stores the deep in reservoirs." The divine sovereignty over the sea — the same waters that threatened chaos at creation (Gen 1:2; Ps 93:3-4) — is exercised by the creator who "gathers" them like a controllable quantity. The NT\'s demonstration of this sovereignty in Christ: Mark 4:39 (Jesus commands the storm — "peace, be still!" — and the wind and sea obey him). The disciples\' response (Mark 4:41: "who is this? Even the wind and the waves obey him!") identifies the one who gathers the sea\'s waters in Ps 33:7 as present in Jesus. The creator\'s relationship to the sea is the Son\'s relationship to the storm.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "Let all the earth fear the LORD; let all who live in the world stand in awe of him." The universal fear-and-awe summons — all the earth, all who live in the world — is the scope of the NT\'s mission: "go and make disciples of all nations" (Matt 28:19); "every knee should bow... and every tongue acknowledge that Jesus Christ is Lord" (Phil 2:10-11). The universal awe of Ps 33:8 is anticipated in creation-sovereignty (v6-7) and will be realized fully at the Parousia when the risen Christ appears as Lord of all. The creation-awe of the psalmist is expanded to include the redemption-awe of those who recognize the Creator as the Redeemer.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "For he spoke, and it came to be; he commanded, and it stood firm." The creative power of divine speech — the fiat of Gen 1 ("God said... and it was so") — is the background for understanding the incarnate Word. If the world was created by divine speech, then the Word-made-flesh (John 1:14) does not merely speak about creation but is the speech through which creation came into being. The authority of Jesus\'s word in the Gospels — commanding spirits, stilling storms, raising the dead — is grounded in the same divine speaking power that Ps 33:9 describes. He who spoke creation into being speaks to the created order from within it.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "The LORD thwarts the purposes of the nations; he brings the plans of the peoples to nothing." The sovereign governance of YHWH over the political designs of nations — the reversal of human strategy — is exemplified supremely in the cross. Acts 4:27-28: "Herod and Pontius Pilate met together with the Gentiles and the people of Israel in this city to conspire against your holy servant Jesus... They did what your power and will had decided beforehand should happen." The nations\' plot to destroy Jesus was the occasion through which YHWH accomplished the redemption of the world: the thwarting of human purposes (the cross intended as a defeat) became the accomplishment of the divine purpose.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "The counsel of the LORD (<em>atzat YHWH</em>) stands forever, the purposes of his heart through all generations." The permanence of the divine purpose — the <em>atzah</em> (counsel, plan, design) that outlasts all human opposition — is the OT foundation for the NT\'s doctrine of election. Ephesians 1:4-5, 11 ("chosen before the creation of the world... predestined according to the plan of him who works out everything in conformity with the purpose of his will") and Romans 8:28-30 ("called according to his purpose... foreknew... predestined... called... justified... glorified") develop the standing-forever counsel of Ps 33:11 into the complete doctrine of divine redemptive purpose. Revelation 13:8 ("the Lamb who was slain from the creation of the world") identifies Christ as the content of that eternal purpose.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: "Blessed is the nation whose God is the LORD — the people he has chosen as his own possession (<em>am segulah</em>)." The <em>am segulah</em> (treasured people, special possession — Exod 19:5; Deut 7:6; 14:2; 26:18; Mal 3:17) is applied in the NT to the church in Christ: 1 Peter 2:9 ("you are... God\'s special possession, that you may declare the praises of him who called you out of darkness into his wonderful light"). The "blessed nation" of Ps 33:12 is now constituted not by ethnic Israel but by those who belong to Christ — the international community of faith that is YHWH\'s <em>segulah</em> through the new covenant in his blood.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "The LORD looks down from heaven; he observes all humanity." The divine omniscience — YHWH surveying all humanity from his heavenly vantage point — is one of the OT\'s foundational theological claims. The NT\'s development: this surveying God has not remained a distant observer but has become a participant in human history through the incarnation. Hebrews 4:13 ("nothing in all creation is hidden from God\'s sight") maintains the divine omniscience, but adds: "everything is uncovered and laid bare before the eyes of him to whom we must give account." The account is given to the one who both sees from heaven (Ps 33:13) and was seen on earth (1 John 1:1: "we have seen with our eyes... we have looked at and our hands have touched").</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "from his dwelling place he surveys all who live on the earth." The divine dwelling place (<em>shevet</em>) from which the survey occurs is the heavenly throne — the same throne from which YHWH\'s sovereignty over nations (v10) and individuals (v13-15) is exercised. Revelation 4-5 is the NT\'s fullest disclosure of this dwelling place: the throne room of heaven, from which the Lamb opens the seals of history. The one who "surveys all who live on the earth" in Ps 33:14 is the one to whom the scroll of history is given in Rev 5:7-9 — "because you were slain, and with your blood you purchased for God persons from every tribe."</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "he who forms the hearts of all (<em>hayotzer yahdav libbam</em>) and considers everything they do." The divine formation of human hearts — the creator\'s intimate knowledge of what he has made — is the basis for the divine understanding of human behavior. Jeremiah 17:9-10: "the heart is deceitful above all things... I the LORD search the heart and examine the mind." The one who "forms the hearts of all" and knows what they do is the judge before whom "we must all appear" (2 Cor 5:10). Christ is both the one who knows what is in humanity (John 2:25: "he knew what was in each person") and the one before whom all hearts are disclosed at the final judgment (Rev 20:12-13).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme: "No king is saved by the size of his army; no warrior is rescued by his own great strength." The reversal of human military logic — that the greatest human resources cannot provide ultimate security — is the OT foundation for Paul\'s theology of divine wisdom through human weakness. 1 Corinthians 1:26-27: "not many of you were wise by human standards; not many were influential; not many were of noble birth. But God chose the foolish things of the world to shame the wise." The cross is the supreme instance of Ps 33:16\'s logic: the salvation of the world was accomplished not by the greatest army but by the death of one person in weakness, which proved to be the power of God (1 Cor 1:18).</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme: "A horse is a vain hope for victory; its great power cannot bring rescue." The horse in the OT is the premier symbol of military power — the instrument of kings (Deut 17:16: kings must not accumulate horses) and empires (Isa 31:1: "Woe to those who go down to Egypt for help, who rely on horses"). The vain trust in horse-power is the inverse of trust in YHWH — and the NT extends this: "not by might nor by power, but by my Spirit, says the LORD Almighty" (Zech 4:6). The Revelation\'s ultimate warrior rides not on a chariot of many horses but as a single rider on a white horse (Rev 19:11-16) — the one whose weapon is the sharp sword of his mouth (the word), not human military force.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "The eye of the LORD is on those who fear him, on those who hope in his steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>)." The divine watchfulness over the faithful — the eye of the surveying LORD (v13-15) now directed with particular care toward the fearers — is the pastoral heart of the psalm\'s sovereignty claim. John 10:27-28: "My sheep listen to my voice; I know them, and they follow me. I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish; no one will snatch them out of my hand." The "eye of the LORD" on the faithful in Ps 33:18 is the Shepherd\'s knowing and protecting of the sheep in John 10 — the sovereign divine gaze exercised as intimate pastoral care.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "to rescue them from death and to keep them alive in famine." The two specific forms of rescue — from death and from famine — are the most basic mortal threats the OT community faced. The NT\'s ultimate rescue from death is the resurrection: "Death has been swallowed up in victory" (1 Cor 15:54-55). The rescue from "famine" takes its most profound form in Christ as the bread of life: "I am the bread of life. Whoever comes to me will never go hungry, and whoever believes in me will never be thirsty" (John 6:35). The physical rescue from death and famine in Ps 33:19 becomes, in Christ, rescue from spiritual death and the eternal satisfaction that no famine can touch.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme: "We wait for the LORD; he is our help and our shield." The posture of waiting — the covenant community oriented toward the future divine action — is one of the Psalter\'s most persistent theological postures. Romans 8:23-25 describes the same posture for the NT community: "we ourselves, who have the firstfruits of the Spirit, groan inwardly as we wait eagerly for our adoption to sonship, the redemption of our bodies." The "help and shield" that the psalm waits for is already partially received in Christ (Eph 6:16: "the shield of faith") but fully awaited at the Parousia. Present waiting and future reception are both genuine dimensions of the "we wait for the LORD" posture.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme: "Our hearts are glad in him, for we trust in his holy name." The gladness grounded in trust rather than circumstances is the NT\'s characteristic description of Christian joy. 1 Peter 1:8: "though you have not seen him, you love him; and even though you do not see him now, you believe in him and are filled with an inexpressible and glorious joy." The "holy name" in which trust rests becomes, in the NT, the name of Jesus: Acts 3:16 ("by faith in the name of Jesus, this man whom you see and know was made strong"); Phil 2:9-10 ("the name that is above every name"). The gladness of Ps 33:21 finds its fullest expression in those whose trust is in the name of the risen Christ.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: "Let your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>), LORD, rest on us, as we have placed our hope in you." The closing petition — for divine covenant love to rest on (<em>al</em>, over, upon) those who hope — is the OT\'s version of what the NT calls "grace." Romans 5:5 ("God\'s love has been poured out into our hearts through the Holy Spirit, who has been given to us") is the Pentecost fulfillment of the <em>hesed</em> petition: the covenant love that Ps 33:22 asks to "rest upon" the people has been poured into their hearts by the Spirit. The hope on which the <em>hesed</em> rests is now, in the NT, hope centered on Christ — "Christ in you, the hope of glory" (Col 1:27).</p>',
  },
}

